ayed by the Qumranic biblical interpetation to the inner-biblical interpretation and the final shaping of the Hebrew scriptures. Moshe Bar-Asher studies cases of such inner biblical interpretative comments; Michael Segal deals with the Garden of Eden story in the scrolls and other contemporary Jewish sources; Reinhard Kratz analizes the story of the Flood as preamble for the lives of the Patriarchs in the Hebrew Bible; Devorah Dimant examines this theme in the Qumran scrolls; Roman Viehlhauer explores the story of Sodom and Gomorrah; George Brooke and Atar Livneh discuss aspects of Jacob’s career; Harald Samuel review the career of Levi; Liora Goldman examines the Aramaic work the Visions of Amram; Lawrence Schiffman and Aharon Shemesh discuss halakhic aspects of stories about the Patriarchs; Moshe Bernstein provides an overview of the references to the Patriarchs in the Qumran scrolls.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aBibelinterpretation. 4aGenesis. 4aPatriarchen. 4aQumran. 4aSchriftrollen vom Toten Meer. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / Old Testament.2bisacsh  aBiblical Interpretation.  aDead Sea Scrolls.  aGenesis.  aPatriarchs.  aQumran.1 aBar-Asher, Moshe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Moshe J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooke, George J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDimant, Devorah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDimant, Devorah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldman, Liora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKratz, Reinhard G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKratz, Reinhard G., eedi